## The Pillow Premium

Every buyer who researches cushion cut engagement rings expecting it to price below princess cut is wrong. The Pillow Premium is the single most consistent surprise in the cushion buying process.

At 1ct GIA Ideal G-VS1, a cushion modified brilliant prices at approximately **$1,891** on Blue Nile. A princess cut at equivalent grade prices in the **$1,600–$1,750** range — roughly 8–12% less. At 2ct, the gap widens: cushion F-VVS2 is **$13,679** versus princess F-VVS2 at approximately **$11,000–$12,000** — a 12–15% premium for the cushion.

The premium exists for two compounding reasons. First, cushion demand has grown steadily for nearly a decade while princess demand has softened — basic supply and demand. Second, cushion rough material requires more precise selection and cutting to achieve the rounded corner geometry while maintaining ideal depth and table percentages; the waste is higher per carat than in princess, where the square geometry is more efficient from rough.

**What this means for buying strategy:** if your budget is fixed and you are considering both princess and cushion, the cushion at your target grade will cost more. The decision is whether the aesthetic difference — soft pillow corners vs sharp geometric corners — is worth the premium to you specifically. For most buyers who choose cushion, it is. But walking in expecting cushion to be the cheaper option leads to sticker shock that affects the entire buying experience.

