### Cushion Cut Pavé Engagement Ring

A pavé cushion cut engagement ring pairs the cushion center stone with a band set with small melee diamonds along the shank. The pavé does not affect the center stone's table presentation — it sits on the band itself — which means pavé avoids The Setting Trap entirely. The result is a ring that appears to sparkle from every angle, not just from the center stone.

**Standard pavé vs micropavé:** Standard pavé uses slightly larger melee stones and is more durable for daily wear. Micropavé uses smaller, more closely set stones for a more delicate appearance. The [Petite Micropavé Hidden Halo 14K White Gold at $1,645](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-micropave-hidden-halo-engagement-ring-item-147511?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) adds a subtle hidden halo beneath the center stone that only becomes visible at certain angles — extra visual interest without the full halo footprint.

[![Cushion cut diamond pavé engagement ring white gold four-prong flat lay](https://ion.bluenile.com/sets/Jewelry/Photoshoot/Bluenile/BrioPackshotBox/Rings/502820/502820_M1_CSH_DIM_wht_0100CT_W_Box5_001_1600X1600.jpg)](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings?ShapeID=Cushion&a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

**Pavé + halo combination:** The most popular cushion engagement ring configuration in {{year}} is a pavé band combined with a square halo — melee on the shank, melee halo around the center, maximum sparkle. This works particularly well with a 1ct–1.5ct lab cushion where the combined visual effect creates the impression of a significantly larger ring than the stone alone would suggest.

