## Metal Choice for Cushion Cut Diamond Engagement Rings

### White Gold (14K or 18K)

White gold is the most popular metal choice for cushion cut diamond engagement rings. The neutral color does not introduce warmth contrast with the stone, making G color appear near-colorless and F-E color appear fully colorless. 14K white gold (58.5% pure gold + palladium alloy) is the practical standard: more durable than 18K, more resistant to scratching, and lower in cost. 18K white gold is softer but carries a higher gold content for buyers who prefer it.

White gold requires rhodium plating maintenance every 1–3 years to maintain its bright white appearance as the plating wears. This is routine and inexpensive — typically $50–$100 per replating.

### Yellow Gold

Yellow gold and cushion cut is a historically authentic pairing — cushion-shaped diamonds were predominantly set in yellow gold throughout the Victorian and Edwardian eras. The warmth of yellow gold works against buyers who need maximum color performance from their stone, but embraces the vintage aesthetic that cushion buyers often seek.

For buyers who choose G or H color stones, yellow gold is a comfortable choice because the slight warmth of G-H color blends with the yellow metal rather than contrasting with it. For buyers who chose D-E-F stones, yellow gold wastes the investment in colorless grades — the metal introduces warmth that the stone was priced to avoid.

### Rose Gold

Rose gold is the fastest-growing metal preference for cushion cut engagement rings. The pink-to-copper warmth of rose gold flatters the cushion's soft, rounded geometry in a way it does not flatter the angular princess or geometric round. For vintage-influenced cushion designs specifically — milgrain, filigree, antique-style — rose gold is the most cohesive metal choice.

The same color consideration as yellow gold applies: rose gold adds warmth. G or H color cushion stones suit rose gold well. D-E-F stones in rose gold pay a premium for colorlessness they will not visually enjoy.

### Platinum

Platinum is the premium metal option for cushion cut diamond engagement rings. It is denser, more durable, naturally white without plating, and hypoallergenic — the only metal for buyers with nickel sensitivity who want a white metal. The [Classic Four Prong Solitaire Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (1,643 reviews) is Blue Nile's most popular platinum setting and typically costs **$400–$700 more** than equivalent 14K white gold settings.

For buyers with high-grade stones (D-E-F, VVS1-VVS2), platinum is the logical setting metal: it will not yellow or require replating, and its density protects high-value stones better over decades of wear. For buyers with G-H stones in the $1,800–$4,000 range, 14K white gold delivers the same visual result for meaningfully less cost.

