> "The most common mistake I see in cushion cut engagement ring purchases is confusing the stone evaluation with the ring evaluation. Buyers find a GIA-certified cushion at a grade they're happy with and assume the work is done. It is not.
>
> The setting decision for a cushion cut diamond is not a style preference — it is a technical decision that determines whether a good stone looks great or looks mediocre on the hand. The table is too open and too directly visible to treat the setting as an afterthought. Get the setting wrong and the certificate becomes irrelevant." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

> "The Pillow Premium is the most consistently surprising fact in the cushion buying process. I have spoken with hundreds of buyers who walked in expecting to pay princess cut prices for a cushion. The premium is structural — it reflects genuine market demand — and it is not going away. Build it into your budget from the first number you write down."

> "For lab-grown buyers specifically: the cushion modified brilliant at 2ct and above is one of the most rational purchases in the diamond market right now. A [2ct D-VVS1 lab cushion at $2,606](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28884982?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) in a halo setting totals under $5,000. That ring looks like a $16,000 natural purchase. The lab certification from IGI is the same scientific process. The only difference is the origin story — and for most buyers in {{year}}, that difference is not worth $13,000." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

